    body: "More than 760,000 Americans collect Social Security payments while living outside the United States, and the Social Security Administration expects that number to keep climbing as more retirees move overseas for warmer weather, lower costs, or to be near family. The good news is that you can keep receiving your monthly retirement, survivors, or disability check in most countries around the world, as long as you set things up correctly before you leave and stay in touch with the SSA after you arrive. The bad news is that a few countries are off-limits for direct payment, and the rules around banking, taxes, and reporting can feel confusing on the first read.\n\nFor Social Security purposes, you are considered to be living outside the United States once you have been outside the country for at least thirty days in a row. At that point, you are an expatriate beneficiary, even if you still own a home in the United States and plan to visit each year. Whether you stay in Mexico for six months, retire in Portugal full-time, or split the year between Florida and Costa Rica, the SSA wants to know where you are and how to pay you. They also want to know that you are still alive, which is why beneficiaries living abroad receive a paper form once a year or every two years called the Foreign Enforcement Questionnaire.\n\nMany retirees worry that moving overseas will somehow cancel their benefits. For United States citizens, that is almost never true. You earned your benefits by paying into the system, and you have the right to receive them no matter where you live, with two main exceptions: Cuba and North Korea. Payments cannot be sent to beneficiaries in those countries, and the SSA holds the money for you until you return to the United States or move to an eligible country. A handful of other countries, like Belarus and parts of Central Asia, have additional restrictions, which is why checking the SSA's Payments Abroad Screening Tool at ssa.gov before your move is the smartest first step.\n\nThis guide walks you through choosing how to receive your money, telling the SSA you are moving, handling banking from abroad, responding to the annual questionnaire, and what to do if your check is late. Set aside about an hour for the planning stage and another thirty minutes for the actual paperwork. If you have not yet started Social Security, do that step first inside the United States; opening a new claim while abroad takes longer and may require a trip to a Federal Benefits Unit at a United States embassy.",
